Colombian Stocks: Bancolombia, Cementos Argos, Enka, Rubiales

-- B y   B l a k e   S c h m i d t
-- 
2011-05-13T16:14:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-13/colombian-stocks-bancolombia-cementos-argos-enka-rubiales.html
The following companies are having
unusual price changes in Bogota trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 11:19 a.m. New York time.  The IGBC Index rose 0.3 percent to 14,314.74, while the
Colcap Index rose 0.2 percent to 1,706.29.  Bancolombia SA (BCOLO)  , the nation’s biggest lender,
dropped 0.9 percent to 28,540 pesos, after topping the list of
Colombian banks that charge the highest ATM fees, El Universal
reported today, citing the country’s financial regulator.  Cementos Argos (CEMARGOS CB),  Colombia ’s biggest cement
maker, rose 1.3 percent to 10,960 pesos after buying assets
yesterday with an enterprise value of $760 million from Lafarge
SA, the world’s biggest cement producer.  Enka de Colombia SA (ENKA)  , a Medellin-based synthetic
fibers producer, rose 2.9 percent to 14 pesos, headed for its
highest close in a month. U.S. Trade Representative Ron Kirk
told a House committee yesterday that a trade agreement would
expand U.S. exports to Colombia by more than $1 billion. Kirk
said the accord will benefit U.S. farmers by eliminating tariffs
on half of current farm exports to Colombia, according to a
statement on the USTR website.  Pacific Rubiales Energy Corp. (PRE)  , the Toronto-based
oil producer that operates fields in Colombia, rose to a 10-day
high after issuing an exploration report late yesterday.  The combined gross production from the Rubiales and Quifa
fields reached a record 207,000 barrels a day, “confirming
the area is the most prolific oil region in Colombia,” the
report
said.  “The exploration update carries significant achievements
in Rubiales and Quifa Southwest fields,” Interbolsa SA,
Colombia’s largest brokerage, said in an e-mailed report today.
“The results are encouraging.”  The stock, which is the second-biggest by weight on the
Colombian exchange after Ecopetrol SA, rose 0.9 percent to
51,800 pesos, the highest since May 3, after climbing as much as
2.1 percent earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
